hority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arbus, Doon}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Reed College alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Artandimage", "label": "safe", "comment": "Inserted manual break in article list", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doon_Arbus"}
{"title_page": "Chronology of computation of \u03c0", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2014}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:Chronology of computation of {{pi}}}}\n{{Pi box}}\nThe table below is a brief chronology of computed numerical values of, or bounds on, the mathematical constant [[pi]] ({{pi}}). For more detailed explanations for some of these calculations, see [[Approximations of \u03c0|Approximations of {{pi}}]].\n{{toc left}}\n[[File:Record pi approximations.svg|thumb|center|800px|Graph showing how the record precision of numerical approximations to pi measured in decimal places (depicted on a logarithmic scale), evolved in human history. The time before 1400 is compressed.]]\n{{clear}}\n\n== Before 1400 ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"| Date\n!align=\"left\"| Who\n!align=\"left\"| Description/Computation method used\n!align=\"right\"| Value\n!align=\"right\"| Decimal&nbsp;places<br />([[world record]]s<br /> in '''bold''')\n|-\n|2000? BC\u0415||Ancient Egyptians<ref name=\"Bailey\">{{cite journal|authors=David H. Bailey, Jonathan M. Borwein, Peter B. Borwein & Simon Plouffe|year=1997|title=The quest for pi|url=http://crd-legacy.lbl.gov/~dhbailey/dhbpapers/pi-quest.pdf|journal=[[Mathematical Intelligencer]]|volume=19|issue=1|pages=50\u201357|doi=10.1007/BF03024340}}</ref>\n|4 &times; ({{frac|8|9}})<sup>2</sup>\n|align=\"right\"|3.16045...||'''1'''\n|-\n|2000? BC\u0415||Ancient Babylonians<ref name=\"Bailey\"/>\n|3 + {{frac|1|8|}}\n|align=\"right\"|3.125||1\n|-\n|1200? BC\u0415||China<ref name=\"Bailey\"/>\n|||align=\"right\"|3||0\n|-\n|800-600 BCE || [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (Sanskrit:\u0936\u0924\u092a\u0925 \u092c\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0939\u094d\u092e\u0923) - 7.1.1.18 <ref>http://mduchin.math.tufts.edu/UCD/111/readings/kak1.pdf</ref>\n||Instructions on how to construct a circular altar from oblong bricks:\n\n''He puts on (the circular site) four (bricks) running eastwards 1; two behind running crosswise (from south to north), and two (such) in front. Now the four which he puts on running eastwards are the body; and as to there being four of these, it is because this body (of ours) consists, of four parts 2. The two at the back then are the thighs; and the two in front the arms; and where the body is that (includes) the head.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Sacred Books of the East: The Satapatha-Brahmana, pt. 3|year=1894|publisher=Clarendon Press|page=303}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>''\n\n(Sanskrit: \"\u0938 \u091a\u0924\u0938\u094d\u0930\u0903 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u091a\u0940\u0930\u0941\u092a\u0926\u0927\u093e\u0924\u093f | \u0926\u094d\u0935\u0947 \u092a\u0936\u094d\u091a\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093f\u0930\u0936\u094d\u091a\u094d\u092f\u094c \u0926\u094d\u0935\u0947 \u092a\u0941\u0930\u0938\u094d\u0924\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0926\u094d\u092f\u093e\u0936\u094d\u091a\u0924\u0938\u094d\u0930\u0903\n\u092a\u094d\u0930\u093e\u091a\u0940\u0930\u0941\u092a\u0926\u0927\u093e\u0924\u093f \u0938 \u0906\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0924\u0926\u094d\u092f\u0924\u094d\u0924\u093e\u0936\u094d\u091a\u0924\u0938\u094d\u0930\u094b \u092d\u0935\u0928\u094d\u0924\u093f \u091a\u0924\u0941\u0930\u094d\u0935\u093f\u0927\u094b \u0939\u094d\u092f\u092f\u092e\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e\u0925 \u092f\u0947\n\u092a\u0936\u094d\u091a\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0924\u0947 \u0938\u0915\u094d\u0925\u094d\u092f\u094c \u092f\u0947 \u092a\u0941\u0930\u0938\u094d\u0924\u093e\u0924\u094d\u0924\u094c \u092c\u093e\u0939\u0942 \u092f\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u0935\u093e \u0906\u0924\u094d\u092e\u093e \u0924\u0926\u0947\u0935 \u0936\u093f\u0930\u0903)\n\n(Sanskrit transliteration: sa catasra\u1e25 pr\u0101c\u012brupadadh\u0101ti | dve pa\u015bc\u0101ttira\u015bcyau dve purast\u0101ttady\u0101\u015bcatasra\u1e25\npr\u0101c\u012brupadadh\u0101ti sa \u0101tm\u0101 tadyatt\u0101\u015bcatasro bhavanti caturvidho hyayam\u0101tm\u0101tha ye\npa\u015bc\u0101tte sakthyau ye purast\u0101ttau b\u0101h\u016b yatra v\u0101 \u0101tm\u0101 tadeva \u015bira\u1e25)\n|alig