 pi|author=|date=|work=pi2e.ch|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n|105 days\n|align=\"right\"|'''22,459,157,718,361'''<br/>{{math|1== {{floor|''{{pi}}<sup>e</sup>''&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;10<sup>12</sup>}}}}\n|-\n|14 March 2019\n|[[Emma Haruka Iwao]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.numberworld.org/blogs/2019_3_14_pi_record/|title=Google Cloud Topples the Pi Record|author=|date=|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref>\n|\n* using [[y-cruncher]] v0.7.6\n* Computation: 1\u00d7 n1-megamem-96 (96 vCPU, 1.4TB) with 30TB of SSD\n* Storage: 24\u00d7 n1-standard-16 (16 vCPU, 60GB) with 10TB of SSD\n* Verification: 1) 20 hours using Bellard's 7-term [[Bailey\u2013Borwein\u2013Plouffe formula|BBP formula]] 2) 28 hours using Bellard's original 4-term BBP formula\n|121 days\n|align=\"right\"|'''31,415,926,535,897'''<br/>{{math|1== {{floor|''{{pi}}''&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;10<sup>13</sup>}}}}\n|-\n|29 January 2020\n|Timothy Mullican<ref>{{cite web|url=http://numberworld.org/y-cruncher/news/2020.html#2020_1_29|title=The Pi Record Returns to the Personal Computer|author=|date=|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blog.timothymullican.com/calculating-pi-my-attempt-breaking-pi-record|title=Calculating Pi: My attempt at breaking the Pi World Record|author=|date=|accessdate=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n|\n* using [[y-cruncher]] v0.7.7\n* Computation: 4x Intel Xeon CPU E7-4880 v2 @ 2.50GHz\n* 320GB DDR3 PC3-8500R ECC RAM\n* 48\u00d7 6TB HDDs (Computation) + 47\u00d7 LTO Ultrium 5 1.5TB Tapes (Checkpoint Backups) + 12\u00d7 4TB HDDs (Digit Storage)\n* Verification: 1) 17 hours using Bellard's 7-term [[Bailey\u2013Borwein\u2013Plouffe formula|BBP formula]] 2) 24 hours using Bellard's original 4-term BBP formula\n|303 days\n|align=\"right\"|'''50,000,000,000,000'''<br/>\n|}\nThe last 100 decimal digits of the latest world record computation are:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.numberworld.org/y-cruncher/records/2020_1_29_pi.txt|title=Validation file|last=|first=|date=7 March 2020|website=N